{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = The Master and His Emissary | title_orig = | translator = | image = The master and his emissary.jpg | caption = Front cover of ''The Master and His Emissary'' | author = Iain McGilchrist | cover_artist = | country = United States and United Kingdom | language = English | series = | genre = [[Psychology]], [[neuroscience]], [[philosophy of mind]], [[sociocultural evolution]] | publisher = [[Yale University Press]] | release_date = 30 October 2009 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]]) | pages = 608 pp. | isbn = 0-300-14878-X | isbn_note = (hardback edition) | oclc= | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''The Master and His Emissary: The Divided Brain and the Making of the Western World''''' is a 2009 book written by [[Iain McGilchrist]] that deals with the specialist [[Lateralization of brain function|hemispheric functioning]] of the brain. The differing world views of the right and left brain (the "Master" and "Emissary" in the title, respectively) have, according to the author, shaped Western culture since the time of the [[Classical Greece|ancient Greek]] [[Philosophy|philosopher]] [[Plato]], and the growing conflict between these views has implications for the way the modern world is changing.<ref name="BBCRadio4Today">{{cite news | last = Staff | first = | title = Two worlds of the left and right brain (audio podcast) | publisher = ''[[BBC Radio 4]] Today'' | date = 14 November 2009 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/today/hi/today/newsid_8360000/8360221.stm | accessdate = 2009-12-24}}</ref> In part, McGilchrist's book, which is the product of twenty years of research,<ref name="LiteraryReviewGrayling"/> reviews the evidence of previous related research and theories, and based on this and cultural evidence, the author arrives at his own conclusions.
''The Master and His Emissary'' received mostly favourable reviews upon its publication. Critics praised the book as being a landmark publication that could alter readers' perspective of how they viewed the world; [[A. C. Grayling]], however, commented about the book that "the findings of brain science are nowhere near fine-grained enough yet to support the large psychological and cultural conclusions Iain McGilchrist draws".<ref name="LiteraryReviewGrayling">{{cite web | last = Grayling | first = A.C. | authorlink = A. C. Grayling | title = In Two Minds | work = [[Literary Review]] | publisher = | date = December 2009 | url = https://literaryreview.co.uk/in-two-minds | doi = | accessdate = 2009-12-21}}</ref>
''The Master and His Emissary'' was shortlisted for the 2010 [[Bristol Festival of Ideas]] Book Prize,<ref name="BristolFestivalOfIdeas">{{cite web |last = Staff |first = |title = Book Prize |publisher = Bristol Festival of Ideas |year = 2011 |url = http://www.ideasfestival.co.uk/?page_id=40 |accessdate = 2011-10-25 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111007174714/http://www.ideasfestival.co.uk/?page_id=40 |archivedate = 2011-10-07 |df = }}</ref> and was longlisted for the [[Royal Society]] 2010 [[Royal Society Prizes for Science Books|Prize for Science Books]].<ref name="TheRoyalSociety">{{cite web | last = Staff | first = | title = Royal Society 2010 Prize for Science Books Longlist Announced | publisher = [[Royal Society|The Royal Society]] | date = 16 June 2010 | url = http://royalsociety.org/2010-Science-Books-Prize-Longlist-Announced/ | accessdate = 2011-10-25}}</ref>
==Background and influences== In an interview with ''Frontier Psychiatrist'', McGilchrist cites two main influences on his work: the psychiatrist [[John Cutting (psychiatrist)|John Cutting]], and the Chicago psychologist [[David McNeill]]. McGilchrist states: "What I began to see – and it was John Cutting's work on the right hemisphere that set me thinking – was that the difference lay not in what they [the two hemispheres] do, but how they do it."<ref name="FrontierPsychiatrist">{{cite web | last = Staff | first = | authorlink = | title = Interview with Iain McGilchrist | work = Frontier Psychiatrist | date = 4 February 2010 | url = http://frontierpsychiatrist.co.uk/interview-with-iain-mcgilchrist/ | accessdate = 2010-02-05}}</ref> In the same interview, the author explains: "Some very subtle research by David McNeill, amongst others, confirms that thought originates in the right hemisphere, is processed for expression in speech by the left hemisphere, and the meaning integrated again by the right (which alone understands the overall meaning of a complex utterance, taking everything into account)."<ref name="FrontierPsychiatrist"/>
==Synopsis== The 608-page book is divided into an introduction, two parts and a conclusion. In the introduction, McGilchrist states that "there is, literally, a world of difference between the [brain] hemispheres. Understanding quite what that is has involved a journey through many apparently unrelated areas: not just neurology and psychology, but philosophy, literature and the arts, and even, to some extent, archaeology and anthropology."<ref name="Mc_2">{{harvnb |McGilchrist|2009| p=2}}</ref>
===Part One: The Divided Brain=== [[File:Human brain superior-lateral view.JPG|thumb|200px|Superior-lateral view of the brain, showing left and right hemispheres.]]
In "The Divided Brain", McGilchrist digests study after study, replacing the popular and superficial notion of the hemispheres as respectively logical and creative in nature with the idea that they pay attention in fundamentally different ways, the left being detail-oriented, the right being whole-oriented. These two modes of perception cascade into wildly different hemispheric personalities, and in fact reflect yet a further asymmetry in their status, that of the right's more immediate relationship with physical bodies (our own as well as others) and external reality as represented by the senses, a relationship that makes it the mediator, the first and last stop, of all experience.
===Part Two: How the Brain Has Shaped Our World=== In the second part, "How the Brain Has Shaped Our World", the author describes the evolution of Western culture, as influenced by hemispheric brain functioning, from the ancient world, through the [[Renaissance]] and [[Protestant Reformation|Reformation]]; the [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]]; [[Romanticism]] and [[Industrial Revolution]]; to the modern and [[Postmodernity|postmodern]] worlds which, to our detriment, are becoming increasingly dominated by the left brain.
==Reception== The book received mixed reviews in various newspapers and journals. Reviewing ''The Master and His Emissary'' in the ''[[American Journal of Psychiatry]]'', Jacob Freedman wrote the book “valiantly addresses the effect hemispheric asymmetry has had on Western civilization" and that it chronicled "how the left brain's determined [[reductionism]] and the right brain's insightful and holistic approach have shaped music, language, politics, and art."<ref name="AmericanJournalPsychiatryFreedman">{{cite journal | last = Freedman | first = Jacob | authorlink = | title = The Master and His Emissary: The Divided Brain and the Making of the Modern World | journal = [[American Journal of Psychiatry]] | volume = 168 | issue = 6 | pages = 655–656 | publisher = [[American Psychiatric Association]] |date=June 2011 | url = http://ajp.psychiatryonline.org/cgi/content/full/168/6/655 | doi = 10.1176/appi.ajp.2011.11010053 | id = | accessdate = 2011-06-05}}</ref> A review by [[Bryan Appleyard]] in ''[[The Times|Times Online]]'' described the book as suggesting "we are thinking more and more like machines, and risk losing what makes us human",<ref name="TimesOnline2009-11-20">{{cite web | last = Appleyard | first = Bryan | authorlink = Bryan Appleyard | title = Divide and rule: man is the new machine | work = [[The Times|Times Online]] | date = 29 November 2009 | url = http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article6931261.ece | accessdate = 2009-12-21}}</ref> while David Cox in the ''[[Evening Standard]]'' wrote that the author "shows convincingly that the degeneracy of the West springs from our failure to manage the binary division of our brains."
In a positive review in ''[[The Guardian]]'', philosopher [[Mary Midgley]] wrote that the book "points out the complexity, the divided nature of thought itself and asks about its connection with the structure of the brain",<ref name="GuardianMaryMidgley">{{cite web | authorlink = Mary Midgley | last = Midgley | first = Mary | title = The Master and His Emissary: The Divided Brain and the Making of the Western World by Iain McGilchrist | work = The Guardian | date = 2 January 2010 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jan/02/1 | accessdate = 2010-01-02}}</ref> and that "though neurologists may well not welcome it because it asks them new questions, the rest of us will surely find it splendidly thought-provoking".<ref name="GuardianMaryMidgley" /> In another positive review in ''[[Standpoint (magazine)|Standpoint]]'' magazine, Professor Adam Zeman wrote that McGilcrist "extends [the] received wisdom with a hugely ambitious, absorbing and questionable thesis: the two hemispheres have radically contrasting personalities; that they live in a state of creative tension, sometimes declining into open war; and that their struggle for supremacy provides the key to understanding the major cultural movements of human history.<ref>{{cite web|author=Adam Zeman |url=http://standpointmag.co.uk/node/2718/full |title=A Brain of Two Halves &#124; Standpoint |publisher=Standpointmag.co.uk |accessdate=2012-05-06}}</ref> In ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'', [[W. F. Bynum]] wrote: "McGilchrist's careful analysis of how brains work is a veritable tour de force, gradually and skilfully revealed. I know of no better exposition of the current state of functional brain neuroscience."<ref name="TLS_WFBynum">{{cite news | title = On the right: Iain McGilchrist The Master and His Emissary – The divided brain | first = W. F. | last = Bynum | newspaper = [[The Times Literary Supplement]] | publisher = [[News International]] | date = 2 April 2010 | page = 12
}}</ref>
In a mixed review in ''[[Literary Review]]'', [[A. C. Grayling]] wrote that the book was "beautifully written, erudite, fascinating and adventurous", but added that "the findings of brain science are nowhere near fine-grained enough yet to support the large psychological and cultural conclusions Iain McGilchrist draws".<ref name="LiteraryReviewGrayling"/> A negative review in ''[[The Economist]]'' stated that the book resorted to "generalisations of breathtaking sweep" and that the second part of the book "has plainly become untethered from its moorings in brain science".<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.economist.com/node/14959719 |title=The human brain: Right and left |publisher=The Economist |date=26 November 2009 |accessdate=2012-05-14}}</ref> Likewise, Michael Corbalis said of the work, that "Although widely acclaimed, this book goes far beyond the neurological facts." <ref>Corbalis, 2014. [http://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.1001767 Left Brain, Right Brain: Facts and Fantasies]. PLoS One.</ref>
[[Owen Flanagan]] alleged many shortcomings of the book and delivered a dismissive statement: "The fact is, hemispheric differences are not well understood. Neither are patterns over 2,500 years of western history. Trying to explain the ill-understood latter with a caricature of the former does little to illuminate either".<ref>{{cite web|author= Flanagan, Owen |url=https://www.newscientist.com/blogs/culturelab/2009/12/the-left-brain-plot-for-world-domination.php?DCMP=OTC-rss&nsref=online-news|title=The vast left-brain conspiracy |publisher=New Scientist CultureLab blog |date=26 November 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-21}}</ref> McGilchrist wrote scathingly of this review, saying: "But anyone who has read my book and reads that review will realise what a shameful piece of writing it is", picking on what he alleges to be evidence of superficiality and misrepresentation.<ref name="pandaemonium">{{cite news | last = Malik | first = Kenan | title = split brain, split views – debating iain mcgilchrist | publisher = Kenan Malik | work = Pandaemonium | date = 24 February 2013 | url = https://kenanmalik.wordpress.com/2013/02/24/split-brain-split-views-debating-iain-mcgilchrist/ | accessdate = 10 March 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180310113405/https://kenanmalik.wordpress.com/2013/02/24/split-brain-split-views-debating-iain-mcgilchrist/ | archive-date = 10 March 2018 | dead-url = no }}</ref>
